Arsenal manager Mikel Arteta praised the “character, courage and quality” of his team as they strengthened their grip on fourth place in the Premier League with a narrow victory at Aston Villa. Bukayo Saka was the standout player as the Gunners secured a sixth win from seven games to move four points clear of fifth-placed Manchester United with a game in hand.   Lukaku scores to help Chelsea reach FA Cup semi-finals     Saka’s first-half strike earns Arsenal victory at Aston…     Osimhen matches Etoo’s record to secure vital win for Napoli   The England international scored the only goal in the first half with a low drive from the edge of the area after Villa failed to properly clear a cross into the box. “You can see the connection they have. It is phenomenal to watch,” Arteta told BT Sport. “If you want to be a top team, you have to win home and away. We are doing that consistently and we have to continue. We really want [to finish in the top four] and we are going to give it a go.”